 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ufurtivus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Furtivus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Boardfellow</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(12/19/01 8:31:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=720.topic&index=64>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Palimax gives back to the community!</span><hr size=1> The interesting point as raised initially by Palimax and disputed by Yuego is whether it is KS to intentionally engage a mob that someone has already begun casting on.  I'm not talking about honest mistakes (since you can't necessarily tell what mob someone is casting on).  I'm talking about what Yuego admitted doing -- intentionally engaging a mob that he knew someone else was casting on.<br>
<br>
Yuego argues that even if someone has obviously begun casting a mob, if you can gain aggro before the spell lands, then you have a right to the mob and the caster is KSing.  This obviously is a very melee centric point of view.<br>
<br>
Straight from the horse's (Verant's) mouth: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Kill Stealing is defined as the killing of an NPC for any reason that is already fighting or pursuing another player or group without that group's specific permission.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Verant's definition is ambiguous in this regard.  If a wizard begins casting on a mob then arguably the wizard and the NPC are &quot;already fighting.&quot;  If an enchanter mezzes a mob and that mob's hate list is cleared by the mez (small chance but it happens especially at lower levels), does the enchanter have claim to the mob?  No one is on the aggro list in either case but arguably the PC and the NPC are &quot;already fighting.&quot;  The intent is there, it's just a longer time between the act and the result (much like there's a short pause between turning on autoattack and actually attacking).<br>
<br>
As a side note here, players have modified this definition by requiring that the player or group fighting or being pursued be capable of killing the mob (e.g. Lodizal).<br>
<br>
I'm not sure Verant would side with Yuego in this situation.  If he intentionally goes around and engages mobs that a player has already begun casting (as he stated he did in his post), I believe his action would violate Verant's policy (particularly if you invoke the general 'harassment' policy).<br>
<br>
Nevertheless, because this point is ambiguous there's arguments on Yuego's side as well.  However, I still think if I followed someone around and attacked everything he (or she) started casting on, Verant would view that as kill stealing and likely harassment. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/upalimaxsceleris.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Palimax Sceleris</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elder</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(12/19/01 9:27:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=720.topic&index=65>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Palimax gives back to the community!</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The interesting point as raised initially by Palimax and disputed by Yuego is whether it is KS to intentionally engage a mob that someone has already begun casting on. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
